<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-01-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-01-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="656" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d656">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to the
                                    <persName type="to">Duke de Arcos</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-01-24"><hi rend="italic">January 24,
                                1900</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 69.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to advise you that the
                            Secretary of War has received a telegram, dated the 17th instant, from
                            General Otis, stating that the <hi rend="italic">Alicante</hi> with 88
                            Spanish officers and 1,039 enlisted men, released prisoners, sailed for
                            Spain on the 13th instant; that 1,500 are still at Manila awaiting
                            shipment, and that probably 700 will be released in the south.</p>
                        <p>Accept, etc.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>